112-443c-92b5-100d968853ac","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T18:44:50.864Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The dissolve transitions from Alma to an establishing shot of Reynolds’s country house, in effect linking Reynolds’s muse to his home. On a certain level, the tension between the two is driven by Alma’s attempts to integrate into the House of Woodcock. She will supplant Reynolds’s mother,&nbsp;whom the dressmaker associates with the country house, and Cyril as the prime maternal figure in his life.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04616/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:392.34444239291014,69.0966580502211,1296.4849519940913,971.8496122599706"}}}]}]}]}